{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778080786,"nonce":"MT7uTJf96EUB5sAmUVweerFnohI=","title":"Cross-partial nabla^2_{theta delta} L diagnostic","message":"The local gate on whether the controller's parameters can be bent at all by the adversary. Per synthesis_review §6.x.\n\n**Definition:** `∇²_{θδ} L` — the cross-partial of the loss with respect to policy parameters θ and adversary parameters δ. If this is small or zero in any subspace, the gradient cannot push θ along that direction regardless of adversarial pressure.\n\n**Computation:**\n- Reverse-mode `grad_θ L` then JVP w.r.t. δ; column-wise.\n- For `GaussianBumpAdversary` (12 params): ~100k × 12 matrix; ~1–2 minutes per checkpoint.\n\n**Diagnostic value:**\nDistinguishes 'training succeeded but signature structurally absent' from 'training failed because adversary couldn't reach θ'. The cleanest local test for whether the optimization landscape supports robustification at all.\n\n**Lower priority than induced-gain** (~1 sec/checkpoint, scalar). Run cross-partial as follow-up if induced-gain reveals interesting structure or if a candidate fix unexpectedly fails.\n\n**Place at:** `src/rlrmp/analysis/cross_partial.py`.\n\nReferences: synthesis_review §6.x, §11 (diagnostic tier). Umbrella: b557d4e.","files":null}]}